properties.query:
// Author: Mohamed Elgendy
// Source: https://redcanary.com/threat-detection-report/threats/mimikatz/
// Reviewer: Lucas Trainer
//
// Description: Kerberos ticket files (.kirbi) are of interest to adversaries as they can contain sensitive data such as NTLM hashes that can be cracked offline. 
// To perform these attacks, a unique file extension variable is defined within Mimikatz that designates the default extension as .kirbi.
// Modification of files with this extension may be a sign of credential theft. 
//
// Handling guidance: Review the logs and entities involved with the incident. If it's not an authorized security testing, escalate to Endpoint security team for incident response
//
// MITRE ATT&CK Reference: https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1558/
DeviceFileEvents
| where FileName endswith ".kirbi" or PreviousFileName endswith ".kirbi" or FolderPath contains ".kirbi"
| extend Hostname = trim_end(@"\..+",DeviceName)

alertDetailsOverride.alertDescriptionFormat:
Kerberos ticket files (.kirbi) are of interest to adversaries as they can contain sensitive data such as NTLM hashes that can be cracked offline. 

To perform these attacks, a unique file extension variable is defined within Mimikatz that designates the default extension as .kirbi. 

Modification of files with this extension can be a telltale sign that an adversary is in the midst of performing an attack ("Kerberoasting")

InitiatingProcessAccountName: {{InitiatingProcessAccountName}}

FolderPath: {{FolderPath}}

FileName: {{FileName}}
